"'''Right Here Waiting for You 2010'''" ({{zh|s=2010等你来|p=èr líng yī líng děng nǐ lái}}) was a promotional song for [[Expo 2010|Expo 2010 Shanghai China]], composed by Miao Sen ({{zh|缪森}}). It was first released in the 30-day countdown on April 1, 2010.
[[Jackie Chan]], [[Lang Lang]], [[Yao Ming]], [[Yang Lan]], [[Andy Lau]], [[Li Ning (gymnast)|Li Ning]], [[Li Bingbing]], and [[Liu Xiang (hurdler)|Liu Xiang]] appeared in the [[music video]]. <ref name="xinhua20100401">{{cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/culture/2010-04/01/c_13233648.htm |title=Expo song released for 30-day countdown |publisher=[[Xinhua News Agency]] |date=April 1, 2010 |accessdate=21 April 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610001523/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/culture/2010-04/01/c_13233648.htm |archivedate=10 June 2011 |df= }}</ref>
==Plagiarism claims== Allegedly, "Right Here Waiting for You 2010" was [[Musical plagiarism|plagiarized]] from the 1997 Japanese song "Sonomama no Kimi de Ite" ("Stay the Way You Are") by [[Mayo Okamoto]], resulting in its use as the Expo theme being suspended.<ref name="chinapost20100421">{{cite web |url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/china/local-news/shanghai/2010/04/21/253413/Shanghai-Expo.htm |title=Shanghai Expo song cut after plagiarism charges |publisher=[[The China Post]] |date=21 April 2010 |accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref><ref name="asahi20100420">{{cite web |url=http://www.asahi.com/english/TKY201004190344.html |title=Expo song hit by plagiarism rumor |publisher=The Asahi Shimbun |date=20 April 2010 |accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref><ref name="jt20100419">{{cite web |url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20100419a6.html |title=World Expo song halted by plagiarism row|publisher=The Japan Times |date=19 April 2010 |accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref> After discussions with Okamoto's management, a compromise was reached such that "Sonomama no Kimi de Ite" is now the official song of the 2010 Expo.<ref name="jz20100421">{{cite web |url=http://www.japan-zone.com/news/2010/04/21/okamoto_mayo_hit_becomes_2010_expo_tune.shtml |title=Okamoto Mayo Hit Becomes 2010 Expo Tune|publisher=Japan Zone |date=21 April 2010 |accessdate=29 April 2010}}</ref>
